dataElements.name: GL-L1/E: # of individuals receiving information services (ES)
dataElements.displayName: GL-L1/E: # of individuals receiving information services (ES)
dataElements.description:
The number of beneficiaries counted for this indicator is the number of individuals that receive information through a group information service plus the number of individuals who receive information one-on-one for a given quarter. Beneficiaries of radio programs/shows are not counted in this indicator.

Information can be delivered in either groups or one-on-one. In most cases, information is generic and is therefore delivered to a group.   

The basic difference between information and counselling services is that information is generic and not tailored to solve specific problems or needs of an individual or group. Information services do not imply an advice on what is the best solution (viable, sustainable, etc.) to a specific problem. When an individual receives one to one information, very often that individual quickly progresses to counselling services, but not always.

dataElements.name: GL-L3/I: # of individuals receiving counselling services (IDPR)
dataElements.displayName: GL-L3/I: # of individuals receiving counselling services (IDPR)
dataElements.description:
The number of beneficiaries counted for this indicator is the sum of the individual counselling beneficiaries plus those individuals who receive counselling as part of a group. A counselling service for a beneficiary or beneficiary group is defined as the entire set of interactions dedicated to resolving one issue.

Counselling is one-to-one advice to a beneficiary or beneficiary group on how to overcome obstacles to durable solutions, what institutions can assist in addressing protection gaps and/or how to address legal issues, including obtaining their rights and entitlements. In some cases counselling may be provided to a group of beneficiaries that share a specific issue.  

It is a step beyond the provision of general information on durable solutions or rights because it entails a degree of analysis of the problems faced by the specific beneficiary or beneficiary group and provides advice on what is the best possible course of action to solve a particular problem. It may require more than one interaction with the beneficiary or beneficiary group and it may entail making contact with institutions or third parties. 

Please note that counselling is different from legal assistance, including Collaborative Dispute Resolution (CDR) because the former offers one individual or group specific advice while in the latter NRC provides legal assistance either in helping two or more parties with a dispute solve that dispute without having resorting to a formal judicial decision, or by representing a party to a dispute in order to find a solution.

dataElements.name: GL-L5/I: # of individuals receiving legal assistance services (IDPR)
dataElements.displayName: GL-L5/I: # of individuals receiving legal assistance services (IDPR)
dataElements.description:
The number of beneficiaries counted for this indicator is the sum of the individual direct legal assistance beneficiaries plus those individuals who receive legal assistance as part of a group.

A legal assistance case is an NRC intervention that uses legal methodology to solve a problem beyond the provision of information and counselling. NRC takes an active role in representing or assisting the beneficiary.  Legal assistance cases can include disputes between opposing parties resolved by a court, a traditional body, an administrative body or by some equivalent legal process or collaborative dispute resolution process.

A case can involve a claim for a service that is denied or when NRC is representing a client facing a legal obstacle to obtain IDP registration

dataElements.name: GL-L80/I: # of individuals receiving training services (IDPR)
dataElements.displayName: GL-L80/I: # of individuals receiving training services (IDPR)
dataElements.description:
For this indicator, a training service includes all the parts that make up a coherent training program or training product regardless of whether the training service takes one day or takes place over multiple days. Male and female beneficiaries are counted one time for their participation in one training service.  Beneficiaries are counted one time for their participation a coherent training program that takes place over five days, not five times.

Trainings vary in terms of length and the way they are delivered. The difference between training and information is that training uses pedagogical activities to impart high-level knowledge and skills to participants who actively engage in learning, while information does not require the same level of commitment or engagement.

dataElements.name: GL-E2/E: # of teachers trained (EiE)
dataElements.displayName: GL-E2/E: # of teachers trained (EiE)
dataElements.description:
Number of male and female teachers that attend at least 50% of a  training.. 

Teacher training: This refers to any support and capacity building which enables teachers and other education personnel to effectively instruct and assess learners on the curricula. Teacher development programs are based on actual and evolving needs of both teachers and learners. There should be a clear link between the curriculum, learning rights, needs of students and their families, and teacher training and continued teacher support. Teachers and other education personnel should receive periodic, relevant, and structured training according to needs and circumstances. 

Pre-service training refers to the training teachers receive before entering a classroom and beginning to teach. 

In-service training refers to the continued training opportunities given to teachers after they have begun teaching in classrooms.

dataElements.name: GL-E71/E: # of individuals receiving NFI kits (EiE)
dataElements.displayName: GL-E71/E: # of individuals receiving NFI kits (EiE)
dataElements.description: An educational NFI kit is a collection of non-food items (note books, pencils, pens, school bags, registers涌) distributed to beneficiaries in a single bundle to support educational objectives. The distribution of student, teacher and director kits can be included in this category. Normally the distribution of kits complements other education activities for example in a YEP or AE programme. If this kit is then replenished as a part of the same programme we do not count this as another beneficiary
